proof.p:
We also need to know where the vectors \vect{z}_{p-1,j}, 1\leq j\leq s_p live.  First we demonstrate that they are members of \krn{T^{p-1}}. \lteval{T^{p-1}}{\vect{z}_{p-1,j}}
                =\lteval{T^{p-1}}{\lteval{T}{\vect{z}_{p,j}}}
                =\lteval{T^{p}}{\vect{z}_{p,j}}
                =\zerovector  So \vect{z}_{p-1,j}\in\krn{T^{p-1}}, 1\leq j\leq s_p.

Moreover, these vectors are not elements of \krn{T^{p-2}}.  Suppose to the contrary that \vect{z}_{p-1,j}\in\krn{T^{p-2}}.  Then \zerovector
                =\lteval{T^{p-2}}{\vect{z}_{p-1,j}}
                =\lteval{T^{p-2}}{\lteval{T}{\vect{z}_{p,j}}}
                =\lteval{T^{p-1}}{\vect{z}_{p,j}} which contradicts the earlier statement that \vect{z}_{p,j}\not\in\krn{T^{p-1}}.  So \vect{z}_{p-1,j}\not\in\krn{T^{p-2}}, 1\leq j\leq s_p.

Define a new subspace of \krn{T^{p-1}} by Q_{p-1}=
                \spn{\set{
                \vectorlist{u}{n_{p-1}},\,
                \vect{z}_{p-1,1},\,\vect{z}_{p-1,2},\,\vect{z}_{p-1,3},\,\dots,\,\vect{z}_{p-1,s_p}
                }} By Theorem there exists a subspace of \krn{T^{p-1}} which will pair with Q_{p-1} to form a direct sum.  Call this subspace R_{p-1}, so by definition, \krn{T^{p-1}}=Q_{p-1}\ds R_{p-1}.  We are interested in the dimension of R_{p-1}.  Note first, that since the spanning set of Q_{p-1} is linearly independent, \dimension{Q_{p-1}}=n_{p-2}+s_p.  Then 
                    \dimension{R_{p-1}}&=\dimension{\krn{T^{p-1}}}-\dimension{Q_{p-1}}
                    &=n_{p-1}-\left(n_{p-2}+s_p\right) =\left(n_{p-1}-n_{p-2}\right)-s_p =s_{p-1}-s_p
                  Notice that if s_{p-1}=s_p, then R_{p-1} is trivial.   Now choose a basis of R_{p-1}, and denote these s_{p-1}-s_p vectors as \vect{z}_{p-1,s_p+1}, \vect{z}_{p-1,s_p+2}, \vect{z}_{p-1,s_p+3}, \dots, \vect{z}_{p-1,s_{p-1}}.  This is another occassion to notice that we have some freedom in this choice.

We now have \krn{T^{p-1}}=Q_{p-1}\ds R_{p-1}, and we have bases for each of the two subspaces.  The union of these two bases will therefore be a linearly independent set in \krn{T^{p-1}} with size 
                    \left(n_{p-2}+s_p\right)+\left(s_{p-1}-s_p\right)&=n_{p-2}+s_{p-1}=n_{p-2}+n_{p-1}-n_{p-2}
                    &=n_{p-1}=\dimension{\krn{T^{p-1}}}
                  So with the proper size the following set is a basis of \krn{T^{p-1}},\set{
                \vect{u}_1,\,\vect{u}_2,\,\dots,\,\vect{u}_{n_{p-2}},\,
                \vect{z}_{p-1,1},\,\vect{z}_{p-1,2},\,\dots,\,\vect{z}_{p-1,s_p},\,
                \vect{z}_{p-1,s_p+1},\,\vect{z}_{p-1,s_p+2},\,\dots,\,\vect{z}_{p-1,s_{p-1}}
                }  We built up this basis in three parts, we will now split it in half.  Define the subspace Z_{p-1} byZ_{p-1}=\spn{B_{p-1}}=
                \spn{\set{
                \vect{z}_{p-1,1},\,\vect{z}_{p-1,2},\,\dots,\,\vect{z}_{p-1,s_{p-1}}
                }} where we have implicitly denoted the basis as B_{p-1}.  Then  allows us to split up the basis for \krn{T^{p-1}} as C_{p-1}\cup B_{p-1} and write \krn{T^{p-1}}=\krn{T^{p-2}}\ds Z_{p-1}>  Whew!  This is a good place to recap what we have achieved.  The vectors \vect{z}_{i,j} form bases for the subspaces Z_i and right now V=\krn{T^{p-1}}\ds Z_{p}=\krn{T^{p-2}}\ds Z_{p-1}\ds Z_{p}

